In[11]:
df["month"] = df.index.month

monthly_avg_demand = df.groupby("month")["demand"].mean()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
sns.lineplot(x=monthly_avg_demand.index, y=monthly_avg_demand.values, marker="o", color="b")
plt.title("Average Electricity Demand by Month")
plt.xlabel("Month (1 = January, 12 = December)")
plt.ylabel("Average Demand")
month_names = ['January', 'February', 'March', 'April', 'May', 'June', 
               'July', 'August', 'September', 'October', 'November', 'December']
plt.xticks(ticks=range(12), labels=month_names, rotation=45)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

July and August have the highest average demand, while Spring and Fall months have the lowest.The average electricity demand by month clearly shows that July and August have the highest average demand, indicating peak summer consumption. There is likely a second peak is observed in January and December, likely associated with winter heating. The lowest demand typically occurs in Spring and Fall months like April, May, September, and October, representing periods of milder weather with reduced reliance on heating and cooling.

plt.show()

The average electricity demand by day of the week reveals a consistent pattern. Electricity demand is generally higher on weekdays (Monday to Friday) compared to weekends (Saturday and Sunday). The demand is likely highest during midweek (Tuesday - Thursday) due to full business operations, and lowest on Sunday.

Seasonal Demand Trends

In[18]:
df.index = pd.to_datetime(df.index)

df['month'] = df.index.month


df['season'] = df['month'].apply(lambda x: 
    'Summer' if x in [12, 1, 2] else 
    'Autumn' if x in [3, 4, 5] else 
    'Winter' if x in [6, 7, 8] else 
    'Spring'
)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(x='season', y='demand', hue='season', data=df, palette="magma", order=["Summer", "Autumn", "Winter", "Spring"])
plt.title("Electricity Demand Distribution by Australian Season")
plt.xlabel("Season")
plt.ylabel("Electricity Demand (MW)")
plt.show()

The visualization shows a clear peak in electricity demand during the Winter months (June-August) compared to other seasons, indicating increased heating demand .A secondary peak is likely observed in Summer (December-February). This suggests increased usage of air conditioning during hotter periods.The transition periods of Spring and Fall show relatively lower and stable demand, implying less reliance on temperature-dependent appliances.

The data indicates that electricity demand is slightly higher during school days compared to holidays. This could be attributed to the energy consumption of schools, offices, and related businesses A noticeable drop in demand is expected during extended holiday periods like Christmas or summer breaks.

The most prominent spikes consistently occur during what appears to be the summer months (based on the data context), typically between July and August. This reinforces the earlier observation that peak electricity demand is strongly correlated with hot weather and increased air conditioning usage.

Weather Impact Analysis

Impact of temperature on electricity Demand

In[8]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
sns.scatterplot(x=df["max_temperature"], y=df["demand"])
plt.xlabel("Max Temperature (C)")
plt.ylabel("Electricity Demand (MW)")
plt.title("Impact of Temperature on Electricity Demand")
plt.show()

As temperatures rise above a certain threshold (around 20C-25C), there's a noticeable increase in electricity demand, likely due to increased air conditioning usage. The relationship might become stronger at higher temperatures, indicating a higher sensitivity to extreme heat. There might also be a point at very high temperatures where demand plateaus.

Impact of Solar exposure on Electricity Demand

In[9]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
sns.scatterplot(x=df["solar_exposure"], y=df["demand"])
plt.xlabel("Solar exposure")
plt.ylabel("Electricity Demand (MW)")
plt.title("Impact of Solar exposure on Electricity Demand")
plt.show()

High solar exposure could reduce electricity demand during the day due to solar panel generation, but might increase demand in the evening as people switch back to grid power.

Impact of Rainfall on Electricity Demand

Conclusion

This exploratory data analysis has revealed several important insights into the factors influencing electricity demand.

  • Seasonality: Electricity demand exhibits strong seasonality, with peak demand occurring during the summer months (July and August) due to air conditioning usage and a secondary peak in winter (December and January) driven by heating needs. Demand is lowest during the spring and fall months.
  • Weekday vs. Weekend: Weekdays (especially Tuesday-Thursday) have higher electricity demand compared to weekends, reflecting the energy consumption of businesses, schools, and offices.
  • Temperature Sensitivity: Electricity demand is highly sensitive to temperature, with a clear positive correlation between maximum temperature and demand. As temperatures rise above approximately 20-25C, demand increases significantly.
  • Limited Impact of Rainfall and Solar Exposure: Rainfall appears to have a limited direct impact on electricity demand. The effect of solar exposure is complex and may depend on the time of day.
  • Holiday Effects: Electricity demand tends to be lower on holidays compared to school days, reflecting reduced commercial and institutional activity.
